2

In the writeup I generally defined Euclidean distance for n dimensions and then had an illustration with 2 dimensions. This problem uses only 1 dimension, in which case the Euclidean distance is just the absolute value of the difference of the two values.
mat_dist = abs(mat - mat(1,1))
mat_dist =
0 1.9400 0.7396 0.8460 0.8433 1.0671 1.3874 2.0041 0.1026 0.9154 0.1627 2.7842 2.1415 2.0580 1.0538 3.4338
This is okay too
sqrt((mat-mat(1,1)).^2)

3(a)

ret = imread('~/Dropbox/Research/Teaching/BMI_567_2018/Homework/Assignment1/img_001.ppm');
size(ret)
ans =
605 700 3
The image dimension is 605 x 700 and is stored in RGB format, which is why the 3rd dimension has a size of 3.
min(ret(:))
ans = uint8 0
max(ret(:))
ans = uint8 255
Notice that MATLAB is specifically telling you the value is uint8? As you will have likely learned (by the time you're reading this solution) that's because the data were read in as 8 bit unsigned integers, so the range of values that can possibly be used is 0-255 (or 2^6=256 different integers). See p64 of the Birkfellner book if you want to know more.

3(b)

All three can be used to plot images and there are many differences, so you may have something I don't mention here and that's fine. The imshow() function works well with RGB, binary and grayscale, but will not do well for images with general values. For example, in fMRI the intensity is a measure of brain activation and can be any real valued number. In this case, imshow doesn't work well. With datat that were images in png, jpg, etc, it does a good job displaying the image and has a lot of built in options that imagesc doesn't have. For example, it converts the RGB values in a meaningful way.
The imagesc() function works well with any image, but only scales the image so we can view it on our computer screens (we'll learn more details about this soon). It can work with any values.
image() is bare bones and is simply displaying the values and not really treating them as something that came from an image. This means if the value go beyond what we can see on our computer screens, it won't display well. We'll see examples of this in the future.
These won't look too different since the range is already 0-255 and scaling isn't needed.
imshow(ret)
image(ret)
imagesc(ret)

3(c)

Before imagesc() was automatically combining the rgb values, but now I'm separating them.
subplot(1,3,1)
imagesc(ret(:,:,1))
axis('square')
colormap('gray')
title('Red')
subplot(1,3,2)
imagesc(ret(:,:,2))
axis('square')
colormap('gray')
title('Green')
subplot(1,3,3)
imagesc(ret(:,:,3))
axis('square')
colormap('gray')
title('Blue')

4.

There are likely numerous ways to go about this. I start by generating a matrix of 0s and simply don't iterate throught the first/last rows/columns in my loop.
ret = double(ret);
filt_ret = 0*ret(:,:,1); % Matrix of 0's the same size as ret.
num_a = size(ret,1);
num_b = size(ret, 2);
for a = 2:(num_a - 1)
for b = 2:(num_b - 1)
dat_neighborhood = ret((a-1):(a+1), (b-1):(b+1),1);
filt_ret(a,b) = mean(dat_neighborhood(:));
end
end
filt_ret(1:5, 1:5)
ans =
0 0 0 0 0 0 10.1111 9.8889 10.5556 10.4444 0 10.0000 9.7778 10.0000 10.0000 0 10.2222 10.0000 9.7778 9.5556 0 10.2222 9.7778 9.2222 9.2222
figure
subplot(1,2,1)
imagesc(ret(:,:,1))
axis('square')
colormap('gray')
title('Original')
subplot(1,2,2)
imagesc(filt_ret)
axis('square')
colormap('gray')
title('Filtered')

5(b)

Note, meshgrid is different than ndgrid.
[X, Y]=meshgrid(x,y);
size(X)
ans =
61 61
subplot(1, 2,1)
imagesc(X)
axis('square')
subplot(1,2,2)
imagesc(Y)
axis('square')
The values in x are replicated ny times (over rows), where ny is the number of values in y. Likewise for y, but over columns. Notably, the resulting matrix is ny x nx (not nx x ny as with ndgrid!). Look closely at the following.
x1 = 1:3
x1 =
1 2 3
y1 = 1:5
y1 =
1 2 3 4 5
[X1, Y1] = meshgrid(x1, y1)
X1 =
1 2 3 1 2 3 1 2 3 1 2 3 1 2 3
Y1 =
1 1 1 2 2 2 3 3 3 4 4 4 5 5 5

It says, "HI":
Z = exp(-(X.^2)-(Y.^2./2)).*cos(4*X) + exp(-3*((X+0.5).^2+Y.^2./2));
Z(Z>0.001)=0.001;
Z(Z<-0.001)=-0.001;
figure
imagesc(Z)

5(d)

The dimensions are the x&y location of the image as well as the pixel intensity. NOT the actual x and y values used.
Range of x dimension is 0 to 61, range of y is 0 to 61 and range of the intensity values is -.001 to 0.001.
size(Z)
ans =
61 61
min(Z(:))
ans = -1.0000e-03
max(Z(:))
ans = 1.0000e-03
